I managed to get my hands on an interesting data set that I want to analyze this time on long past due with PySpark. As my current Azure trial account will expire later this month, I will take advantage of my still available free subscription and use a free tier Azure Databricks Cluster. So, letâ€™s dive into a Spark notebook session right away.

For this data set about trains in Belgium, I do not have any metadata available, besides the header row inside the file itself. The set is not that large both feature or records-wise; as we will find out later the limited scope of features means that these are insufficient in explaining enough variance of any 'delay labeled' column, be it regression or classification framed problem. In praxis, such a barebone data set will have to be complemented with further data from various sources, e.g. data from business systems, IoT sensor data in trains and stations, and external data sources like e.g. local/regional weather data, provided by our goal of the analysis is the finding of correlating features with train delays and possible insights about root causes with proven causal relationships.

  .option("sep", delimiter) \
  .load(file_location)

display(df)

from pyspark.sql import functions as F

def create_timestamps_date_time_cols(df, date_col, time_col):
  """Combine date and time cols and convert to datetime"""
  from pyspark.sql import functions as F
  spark.sql("set spark.sql.legacy.timeParserPolicy=LEGACY")
  df = df.withColumn(time_col + '_ts', F.concat_ws(' ', date_col, time_col))
  df = df.withColumn(time_col + '_ts', F.to_timestamp(time_col + '_ts', 'yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss'))
  return df

While the two operators SNCB/NMBS and THI-FACT have much less trains going their empirical cumulative distribution function shows that a lot fewer trains having large delays accumulated and these delays are less excessive.

All operators have in common that their median train show about the same slight delay on Arrival; all functions meet and cross themselves at a ratio between 0.5 and 0.6.

![png](/blog/belgian-train-times_files/belgian-train-times%20for%20blog_31_0.png)
    


The busiest train stations usually have trains arriving with a delay. From these the stations in Antwerpen stand out for having a quite limited total delay or even a median below zero, where more than 50% of the trains arrive with no delay at all.

The other busy station standing out is "Ottignies" which shows the highest variance of delays with the largest interquartile range as well the longest wicks on its boxplot. Here the median delay is by far the highest observed among all busy train stations.


```
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(20,10)})
sns.boxplot(data=plot_df[plot_df['Stopping place'].isin(top_stopping_places_list)], x='Stopping place delay delta', y="Stopping place", order=top_stopping_places_list)

plt.axvline(x=0, linestyle='--', color='black')
plt.xlim(-400,400)
#plt.yticks(np.arange(0, 1, step=0.1))
plt.title('How do the busiest train stoppping stations add to or catch up on train delays? (Top 20 of busiest train stations)')
plt.ylabel('Train stopping place')
plt.show()
```


    
![png](/blog/belgian-train-times_files/belgian-train-times%20for%20blog_33_0.png)
    


Having earlier called out "Ottignies" for its delay problem of trains arriving, looking at its stopping place delay numbers that on median trains leave the station early cathing on delays more often than not, but while still observing a high variance.
So "Ottignies" is inheriting the delays mostly and not particularly adding to it.

Antwerpen stations stand out here again, by mostly adding to delays, as opposed to most other stations in this scope.

While there are train stations which are consistent in not adding to delays with a interquartile range completely below the zero line (e.g. Train Stop "Gedinne"), all in the top 10 stations have a median train stop that is reducing delay by having a 'Stopping place delay delta' less than zero.

from pyspark.ml import Pipeline

# Create list of StringIndexers

# Create pipeline of indexers
indexer_pipeline = Pipeline(stages=indexers)

# Fit and Transform the pipeline to the original data
df_indexed = indexer_pipeline.fit(df).transform(df)

# Clean up redundant columns

# Create a confusion matrix
predictions.groupBy("label", "prediction").count().show()

# Calculate the elements of the confusion matrix
TN = predictions.filter('prediction = 0 AND label = prediction').count()
TP = predictions.filter('prediction = 1 AND label = prediction').count()
FN = predictions.filter('prediction = 0 AND label <> prediction').count()
FP = predictions.filter('prediction = 1 AND label <> prediction').count()

print(TN, TP, FN, FP)
# Accuracy measures the proportion of correct predictions
accuracy = (TP +TN )/ (TP + TN +FN +FP)
print(accuracy)

from pyspark.ml.evaluation import MulticlassClassificationEvaluator, BinaryClassificationEvaluator

# Calculate precision and recall
precision = TP / (TP + FP)
recall = TP / (TP + FN)
print('precision = {:.2f}\nrecall    = {:.2f}'.format(precision, recall))

# Find weighted precision
multi_evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator()
weighted_precision = multi_evaluator.evaluate(predictions, {multi_evaluator.metricName: "weightedPrecision"})

# Find AUC
binary_evaluator = BinaryClassificationEvaluator()
auc = binary_evaluator.evaluate(predictions, {binary_evaluator.metricName: "areaUnderROC"})

![png](/blog/belgian-train-times_files/Snapshot_2022-10-12_213306_adb-8327043797808427.7.azuredatabricks.net.png)

As indicated right from the start is the data set as given unsuited to be analyzed by a machine learning model, as the limited scope of features (with a large proportion of categorical ones) is unable to adequately explain the delay variance at all. That just means that more data from other sources should be considered to be added, which can further augment the given and already feature-engineered data columns as shown above. Any railway company can easily provide further train and station-related data from their operational systems such as railway section utilization data in a large quantity, so that you can easily incorporate train number specific data to even have train number (group) specific models created that are more homogeneous among themselves and allow better estimates/outputs. In praxis, such a barebone data set will have to be complemented with further data from various sources, for instance, data of business systems, IoT sensor data in trains and stations, and external data sources like e.g. local/regional weather data, provided the goal of the analysis is the finding of correlating features with train delays and possible insights about root causes with proven causal relationships.

Therefore, I focused on rather explorative data analysis especially the timing and delay features and of course how the train stations relate to delays. 

There were some interesting findings and I hope you enjoyed following as much as I did.
